<font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">
>>remember, +100 dex has like a 5% effect on proc rate<P>One flaw with this dex argument... you're looking at it from a chance to proc per swing.  There, yes, going from 100 to 255 dex can mean you proc on 10% instead of 5% of swings.  But 5% vs 10% is a 100% increase in proc rate.  Now, if someone said "dex doubles your chance to prc"... it would sound like it is worth it.  But would it be?  Much of that would depend upon the initial proc rate of the weapon, wouldn't it?<P>The same thing applies to cha.  How people look at the reduction of resist rate in tests (as the difference in resist rates) without considering the other side (as the percentage resists are reduced) combined with the tendency of tests to be performed on very easy to mez mobs means that most people's interpretation of test results is flawed.<P>This means that they see 6 resists out of 100 reduced to 4 out of 100 and think a 2% reduction.  Doesn't work that way.  If you are facing 60 resists out of 100, you don't drop to 58 out of 100.  In that situation, your resist rate will be impacted a lot more.<P>Does that mean I'm saying cha is worth it?  Nope, it doesn't.  I'm not going to make decisions for people.  That's something for them to figure out themselves.  <P>There's quite a few factors to consider.  From how often we are asked to mez things that resist that often to alternative strategies that can be applied to get the job done without needing more cha to discrepencies in the resist rate.  And, of course, an important consideration... the fact that most of us don't have super low cha.  The difference is rarely 100 vs 255.  With very minimal effort, most of us have 170+ cha.  There's a minimal cost to get a certain amount of charisma.  And a much higher cost to get more.<P>It's a personal decision for every enchanter to make at various parts of their career.  I think most that bother to do some research and experiment will end up focused quite a bit on hp/ac.  But I also think that most will see there is enough merit to cha to keep the stat at somewhat of a decent level.
<br />&nbsp;
</font>
